  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Will 8 RAC tickets that have changed to CNF, get adjacent berths?",
  "response": "When your 8 RAC (Reservation Against Cancellation) tickets convert to CNF (Confirmed) status, whether you receive adjacent berths depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Seat Availability**: The primary factor is the number of available berths in the train at the time of confirmation. If there are enough adjacent berths free, the system may allocate them to your group.\n\n2. **Train Class**:\n   - **Sleeper Class (SL)**: Generally offers more flexibility and a higher number of berths, increasing the chances of getting adjacent seats.\n   - **AC Classes (3AC, 2AC, etc.)**: These classes have fewer compartments and berths, so adjacent allocations might be more challenging but still possible.\n\n3. **Timing of Cancellation**: If cancellations happen close to the departure time, there might be limited opportunities to rearrange or allocate berths adjacently. Earlier confirmations might improve the chances.\n\n4. **Group Booking**: If all 8 RAC tickets are booked under a single Passenger Name Record (PNR), there is a higher likelihood of receiving adjacent berths compared to individual bookings.\n\n5. **Railway's Allocation System**: The automated reservation system manages berth allocations based on availability and booking sequence. While it strives to accommodate passenger preferences, simultaneous allocations depend on real-time seat mapping.\n\n**Tips to Increase Chances of Adjacent Berths:**\n\n- **Book Together**: Try to book all seats in one transaction under a single PNR.\n- **Check Reservation Chart**: Keep an eye on the online reservation chart updates through the IRCTC website or app as the departure date approaches.\n- **Use Sleeper or AC3 Class**: These classes generally have better chances for adjacent allocations due to more flexible berth arrangements.\n- **Contact Railway Authorities**: In some cases, speaking directly with railway staff at the station might help in arranging adjacent berths, especially if you\u2019re traveling with a group.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nWhile there is a possibility of obtaining adjacent berths when multiple RAC tickets convert to CNF, it is not guaranteed. It largely depends on the factors mentioned above. Planning ahead and keeping track of your booking status can improve your chances of securing adjacent seats.",
